ind,\nThey pass and have left no traces;\nBut one of them lingers far behind\nThe flight of the fairy faces.\nHhe makes no moan.\nShe sorrow* in the dark alone,\nHhe wails for the love of human kind,\nLike a whistling wind.\n\"Ah! why did I roam where the elfns ride,\nTheir glimmering steps to follow?\nThey bore me far away from my loved one's aide.\nTo wander o'er hill and hollow, I\nKling' Klang' Kling!\nTheir stirrups and bridles ring.\nBut my heart la cold in the cold night-tide,\nI\nWhere the elfns ride.\"\nAtlanta Constitution.\n1\nI\nl\nThe price of PKEa Indicates that it eonts morel\nto raise a hen that it used to cost to fatten a hos.\nWe al object if the market condition is against I\nua, but we ue not concerned as long as things!\ngo our way.\nWho sayc the price of necessities is not coming'.\ndow n?\nJust note what is happening to the coat!\nof automobiles.\ni\nThe trees are not all properly\ntinted\nfor\nI\nautumn, but you can notice some beautiful col\nors on some of them.\nA joint debate interests the debater* anyway.\nA lot of difference Is noted between the man\nwho works while he thinks and the oue\ndoes nether.\nwho1\n4\nI\nt\nHo far the right of suffrage does not seem to\nhave interfered in any appreciable wa with the\nnormal progress of the wedding march. Balti\nmore American.\nt\nMr. Barnum may have been\nwronk.\nbut\nsi\nseems certain that on an important thing people1\n\nwould rather take chances than depend\ncertain foundation.\non\nThe friends of Cox say he settled two points\nwhile on his western tour; but they might net\nagree with the republicans about the two things\nhe definitely settled.\nt\n\nI\nHo much attention is being given to the discus\nIon of the league of nations that the state and*\nnational administration has no time to be con\ncerned about coal for the winter needs.\nI\nWith all the corn we note in the fields, and the\nfact that none of It will be required for boose,\nwe ought to have plenty of corn bread this win\nter and